{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":21984,"name":"Haolly","username":"haolly","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/haolly/{size}/1041_2.png","created_at":"2017-11-25T12:06:03.860Z","cooked":"\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"lang-auto\"\u003e// Make a copy of the context pointer in case the object is destroyed during event handler invocation\n    Context* context = context_;\n    EventHandler* specific = nullptr;\n    EventHandler* nonSpecific = nullptr;\n\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe comment “Make a copy …” really confuse me,  the code \u003ccode\u003eContext* context = context_\u003c/code\u003e really is a pointer assignment,\u003cbr\u003e\nthe content of \u003cem\u003econtext_\u003c/em\u003e is not  copied to \u003cem\u003econtext\u003c/em\u003e , so if \u003ccode\u003econtext_\u003c/code\u003e is destroyed , say \u003ccode\u003econtext_ = nullptr\u003c/code\u003e, so \u003ccode\u003econtext\u003c/code\u003e is also\u003cbr\u003e\nbe invalid to use, because they are point to the same address.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIt will be appreciate if someone explain the code a bit more.\u003cbr\u003e\nI recently wanted to learn an open source game engine, so I try to read the source and fing out what it was doing.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-11-25T15:45:52.141Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":28,"readers_count":27,"score":15.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":3784,"topic_slug":"could-someone-please-explain-the-function-object-onevent","display_username":"Haolly","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":877,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":21985,"name":"Eugene Kozlov","username":"Eugene","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png","created_at":"2017-11-25T12:27:15.439Z","cooked":"\u003caside class=\"quote\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"3784\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/haolly/40/1041_1.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e haolly:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIt will be appreciate if someone explain the code a bit more.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eContext is considered as immortal object among any other \u003ccode\u003eObject\u003c/code\u003es, so it’s never destructed in any function.\u003cbr\u003e\nHowever, event processing could destroy \u003cem\u003ethe object\u003c/em\u003e, so \u003ccode\u003econtext_\u003c/code\u003e become invalid.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf you have small quetions like this, it’s probably makes sence to ask them \u003ca href=\"https://gitter.im/urho3d/Urho3D\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003ehere\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-11-25T12:38:48.494Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":28,"readers_count":27,"score":10.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":3784,"topic_slug":"could-someone-please-explain-the-function-object-onevent","display_username":"Eugene Kozlov","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://gitter.im/urho3d/Urho3D","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"urho3d/Urho3D - Gitter","clicks":11}],"read":true,"user_title":"Core developer","title_is_group":false,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":484,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":22038,"name":"Haolly","username":"haolly","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/haolly/{size}/1041_2.png","created_at":"2017-11-27T12:02:09.709Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eEugene , thanks for you reply.\u003cbr\u003e\nYou mean the event receiver itself may be destroyed during event processing?\u003cbr\u003e\nIs there Only one \u003ccode\u003eContext\u003c/code\u003e object living in the whole lifetime of the engine run time ?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eGitter is a good place,  I will  post my left small question there to see if it would be overwhelmed by others discussions\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-11-27T12:02:09.709Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":21,"readers_count":20,"score":9.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":3784,"topic_slug":"could-someone-please-explain-the-function-object-onevent","display_username":"Haolly","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"username":"Eugene","name":"Eugene Kozlov","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":877,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":22040,"name":"Eugene Kozlov","username":"Eugene","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png","created_at":"2017-11-27T13:01:09.219Z","cooked":"\u003caside class=\"quote\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"3784\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/haolly/40/1041_1.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e haolly:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou mean the event receiver itself may be destroyed during event processing?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eExactly.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003caside class=\"quote\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"3784\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/haolly/40/1041_1.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e haolly:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIs there Only one Context object living in the whole lifetime of the engine run time ?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn most cases you don’t need more that one context.\u003cbr\u003e\nThere is nothing wrong in creating and using multiple ones tho.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHowever, I don’t recommend to run multiple instances of the engine in separate contextes, because it’s only theoretically working and almost untested.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn summary, you could use as much contextes as you need, but don’t create more than one \u003ccode\u003eEngine\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2017-11-29T06:34:07.318Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":20,"readers_count":19,"score":14.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":3784,"t